4 Steps To Protect Your Online Reputation: Tom Desmond iSEOi

It doesn't matter if you’re famous or not…you may be part of some obscure group, or you might be a household name.. guess what? You are being searched right now, so it's wise to protect your online reputation.

Politicians, corporations, and employers have unparalleled access to your history, networks, and more. A recent survey stated that 78% of recruiters - potential employers and prospective colleges - are using Google to check on candidates before making big decisions, and a few negative comments can determine your fate. This is why diligent online reputation management is an indispensable tool.  Staying active with online reputation management pays off, protecting you from false or damaging search results. Since the Internet is hear to stay, online reputation management is something you will have to do forever.

1. Buy domain names - You can buy a domain name from GoDaddy for about $9 a year. This is a good start. If your name is taken, try a few alterations: add your middle initial (JohnPDow.com), add your business name (JohnDowConstruction.com), add your craft: (JohnDowPhotography.com). At least you'll have your name in the root URL.
2. Create a blog or website with your new domain - install WordPress to your domain and begin to create pages optimized for your name. Make sure your name is in the page title and description first, then write about 300-350 words of text with a keyword density of 2% or 3%. Create a few posts every week, because Google loves fresh content.
3. Become a contributor for other blogs - make sure you include a link back to your blog/website and also include your name in the post. Backlinks improve the authority of your site and including your name in the post strengthens the attachment of your name to positive content.
4. Write and submit press releases and articles - these are similar to blog posts in that they count as quality backlinks to your site, plus they're are longer, more informative, and can get picked up by other bloggers or journalists. - a very good thing indeed.

Jump out there first and control what the Internet has to say about you. Many doctors have patients that like to attack them online. We're all in this ever-interconnected social environment, and our identities are fragile.
